    "recap_headline": "Princeton University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "PRINCETON, N.J. -\nThe Tigers sweep Cornell in a doubleheader to open up their first series at Clarke Field this season, against Cornell.\nPrinceton 13, Cornell 7\nPrinceton opened up the scoring in the second inning off of an RBI single from\nTommy Googins\n.\nThe Tigers continued to put up five more runs in the third inning, making it 6-0, with\nJake Koonin\nhitting a three run homerun, followed by a RBI single from\nJake Kernodle\n.\nOffensive noise only got louder in the fifth inning as Princeton went on to score seven runs, increasing the lead to 13-0.\nCornell was able to chip away at the deficit in the ninth inning, scoring seven runs.\nJustin Kim\nstarted on the mound, picking up his second win, after an impressive five-inning outing where he did not allow any runs and punched out eight.\nWill Sword\nstruck six in four relief frames for the Tigers.\nPrinceton 12, Cornell 0\nThe Tigers opened up, scoring off the bat in the first with a sacrifice fly from\nBennett Crerar\nfollowed by another\u00a0homerun from Koonin.\nPrinceton continued to put up three more runs in the second inning.\nIn the fourth inning, an RBI triple off the bat of Crerar made it a 6-0 game.\nThe Tigers tallied up two more runs in the sixth inning, scoring on an error by Cornell followed by a RBI single from\nTomas Cernius\n.\nAfter putting up two more runs in the seventh,\nWill Robbins\nadded to the lead with a two-run homerun in the eighth inning, making it 12-0.\nJames Beasley\ntook the start on the mound for the Tigers, going five frames while striking out four.\nElliott Eaton\nearned the save with four scoreless innings.\nThe Tigers and Big Red finished off the series on Sunday. First pitch is scheduled for 12 p.m.",
